To Munatius Plancus, [noox 1.

Cive me Anio's headlong torrent, And Tiburnus' grove and hills,

And its orchards 'sparkling dewy With a thousand wimpling rills 2

As the sunny south wind often Sweeps the louring clouds away, Nor with showers unceasing ever Loads the long and dreary day, Plancus, so do thou remember Still to cheer with balmy wine All the care and grief and travail Of this toilworn life of thine 3 Whether in the thronged camp, gleaming With a thousand spears, or laid On the turf beneath the umbrage , Of thy loved Tiburtine glade. ” ’
